<subSubSection id="C30CE68AFF96FF59FF4A8A93E5CBF9F0" lastPageId="72" lastPageNumber="73" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BA9B501FF96FF56FF4A8A93E528F9A5" blockId="71.[151,1437,1117,2008]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
<emphasis id="B9626913FF96FF56FF4A8A93E61BFA1A" bold="true" box="[199,337,1441,1467]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Description</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF96FF56FEEC8A93E6D4FA1A" box="[353,414,1441,1467]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Head</emphasis>
with blunt anterior projection, dorsal and anterior margins straight, 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF96FF56FB2E8A90E3B1FA1A" box="[1187,1275,1442,1467]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">rostrum</emphasis>
apex rounded with tiny setules. 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF96FF56FED08AF7E5C0FA7E" box="[349,650,1477,1503]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Interantennal head margin</emphasis>
vertical, lower corner broadly rounded. 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF96FF56FBC38AF4E217FA7E" box="[1102,1373,1477,1503]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Eyes and assessory eyes</emphasis>
present (lenses reduced to lump in 
<typeStatus id="54AD0BA3FF96FF56FE628ADBE51CF9A5" box="[495,598,1513,1540]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">holotype</typeStatus>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA9B501FF96FF56FF4A893FE616F9EA" blockId="71.[151,1437,1117,2008]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
<emphasis id="B9626913FF96FF56FF4A893FE665F986" box="[199,303,1549,1575]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Pleonites</emphasis>
1 and 2 with very fine irregular serration on lower half of posterior margin. 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF96FF56FBFE893CE3B9F986" box="[1139,1267,1550,1575]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Urosomites</emphasis>
1–3 with small dorsodistal spine.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA9B501FF96FF56FF4A8967E37BF932" blockId="71.[151,1437,1117,2008]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
<emphasis id="B9626913FF96FF56FF4A8967E600F9CE" box="[199,330,1621,1647]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Mouthparts</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF96FF56FEDA8967E6B3F9CE" box="[343,505,1621,1647]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Maxilla 1 palp</emphasis>
apex with 4 finely denticulate peg-like setae and 1 lateral and 1 medial more slender seta, 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF96FF56FF5C8948E601F932" box="[209,331,1657,1683]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">outer plate</emphasis>
with 9 sharply pointed spine-setae. Mouthparts otherwise normal.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA9B501FF96FF56FF4A89ACE60CF8E9" blockId="71.[151,1437,1117,2008]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
<emphasis id="B9626913FF96FF56FF4A89ACE672F916" box="[199,312,1693,1720]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Antenna 1</emphasis>
as long as pereonite 1–7 combined along dorsum, sparsely setose, peduncle article 2 about half length of 1, article 3 about 1/3 longer than article 2, 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF96FF56FD1089F3E44DF97A" box="[669,775,1729,1755]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">flagellum</emphasis>
about 1.25 length of peduncle, with 14 articles, 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF96FF56FAA389F0E64BF95E" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">accessory flagellum</emphasis>
of 2 articles. 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF96FF56FE1189D4E544F95E" box="[412,526,1765,1792]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Antenna 2</emphasis>
as long as pereonites 1–7 and half of pleonite 1 combined along dorsum, peduncular article 4 the longest with dense row of setae on anterior margin, 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF96FF56FC3D883BE350F882" box="[944,1050,1801,1827]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">flagellum</emphasis>
of 14 articles; antennae otherwise sparsely setose.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA9B501FF96FF56FF4A8863E473F876" blockId="71.[151,1437,1117,2008]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
<emphasis id="B9626913FF96FF56FF4A8863E616F8CA" box="[199,348,1873,1899]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Coxal plate 1</emphasis>
distally widening, anterior margin with blunt mid-anterior projection, 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF96FF56FBEA8863E3F8F8CA" box="[1127,1202,1873,1899]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">plate 2</emphasis>
longer than 1, nearly rectangular with weak mid-anterior concavity. plate 3 strongly pelagont, posterior projection broadly rounded, with short 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF96FF56FF5B88ABE669F812" box="[214,291,1945,1971]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">plate 4</emphasis>
about as long as broad, anteriorly and distally rounded, posterior margin with weak concavity, 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF96FF56FAC288ABE2D6F815" box="[1359,1436,1945,1972]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">plate 7</emphasis>
about twice as long as greatest depth, slightly posterolobate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA9B501FF99FF59FF4A8FA5E619FDB8" blockId="72.[151,1437,151,1941]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FF4A8FA5E6D5FF10" box="[199,415,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Gnathopod 1 basis</emphasis>
length about 6 times width, 1.2 length of carpus, anterior margin with long and medium setae, posterior margin with a couple of medium setae, 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FC9C8F89E422FF74" box="[785,872,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">ischium</emphasis>
with posterodistal tuft of setae, 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FB578F89E254FF75" box="[1242,1310,187,212]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">merus</emphasis>
with some long setae in posterior distal half, 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FD9F8FEDE514FF59" box="[530,606,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">carpus</emphasis>
about 5 times longer than greatest width, posterior margin with row many setae of varying length, dorsal margin with 1 long setae in middle and 
<quantity id="4CEE18E4FF99FF59FC4A8E31E4BEFEBC" box="[967,1012,259,285]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.54" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" unit="in" value="1.0">1 in</quantity>
distal corner, 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FB158E31E24BFEBC" box="[1176,1281,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">propodus</emphasis>
0.6 length of carpus with 3 stout, pectinate setae and some simple setae on posterior margin, 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FB878E15E32DFEE0" box="[1034,1127,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">dactylus</emphasis>
and unguis of equal length, combined nearly half as long as carpus. 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FDE98E79E471FEC4" box="[612,827,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Gnathopod 2 basis</emphasis>
length 8.0 times width, 1.2 length of carpus, anterior margin with spaced row of about 6 long setae, posterior margin with 4 long setae in proximal half, 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FA868E5DE228FE28" box="[1291,1378,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">ischium</emphasis>
with small posterior tuft of setae, 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FE5A8EA1E551FE0D" box="[471,539,403,428]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">merus</emphasis>
with row of setae in distal third, 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FC028EA1E491FE0D" box="[911,987,403,428]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">carpus</emphasis>
about 10 times longer than wide, posterior margin with spaced row of medium length setae, 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FD638E85E41DFE70" box="[750,855,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">propodus</emphasis>
long and slender, 2/3 the length of carpus, posterior margin with spaced row of about 6 short, stiff setae, 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FD608EE9E400FE54" box="[749,842,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">dactylus</emphasis>
and unguis of subequal length, combined about half length of carpus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA9B501FF99FF59FF4A8D11E6EEFBF8" blockId="72.[151,1437,151,1941]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FF4A8D11E69EFD9C" box="[199,468,546,573]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Pereopods 3–6 dactylus</emphasis>
about as long as broad, nearly fully stubby, dactylus of 7 conical, about twice as long as broad. 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FE8A8D75E6BEFDC0" box="[263,500,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Pereopods 3–4 basis</emphasis>
about 2.5 times longer than wide, about as long as ischium and merus combined, all articles with few short robust setae. 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FDDB8D59E592FD24" box="[598,728,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Pereopod 5</emphasis>
shorter than 6 and 7, basis pear shaped broadest in distal half, 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FF1A8DBDE614FD09" box="[151,350,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">merus and carpus</emphasis>
with few short robust setae. 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FD168DBDE451FD09" box="[667,795,654,681]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Pereopod 6</emphasis>
basis ovoid, posterior margin with slight bulge in middle, anterior margin with a few long setae distally, 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FD2F8D81E5ACFD6D" box="[674,742,691,716]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">merus</emphasis>
posterior margin with single robust seta in middle and 1 long and 1 short in distal corner, anterior margin with 2 short robust setae in middle and 2 of unequal size in distal corner, 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FF1A8DC9E7A9FCB5" box="[151,227,763,788]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">carpus</emphasis>
posterior margin with single robust seta in middle and group of 
<quantity id="4CEE18E4FF99FF59FC468DC9E4B2FCB4" box="[971,1016,763,789]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.62" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" unit="in" value="3.0">3 in</quantity>
distal corner, anterior margin with 4 pairs of unequal robust setae, 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FE618C2DE51FFC98" box="[492,597,799,825]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">propodus</emphasis>
anterior margin with 2 robust setae distally, posterior distal corner with 3 unequally long robust setae. 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FE518C71E514FCFC" box="[476,606,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Pereopod 7</emphasis>
(especially propodus) longer than pereopods 5 and 6, 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FB4A8C71E24BFCFC" box="[1223,1281,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">basis</emphasis>
anterior margin shorter than pereopod 6 basis, 1.4 times wider than anterior margin length, posterior margin forming broadly rounded lobe with tiny setules curving smoothly unto slightly projecting distal lobe, anterior margin with a few long setae distally, medial surface with row of several long setae, 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FCC98C9DE4C2FC69" box="[836,904,943,968]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">merus</emphasis>
posterior margin with 1 long simple seta and 1 robust seta in middle and 1 short and 1 long robust setae in distal corner, 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FC408CE1E353FC4D" box="[973,1049,979,1004]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">carpus</emphasis>
posterior margin with 1 small and 1 long robust seta on distal corner, anterior margin with robust setae; propodus anterior margin with 3 robust setae, posterior distal corner with 3 unequally long robust setae, 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FCAD8B29E437FB94" box="[800,893,1051,1077]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">dactylus</emphasis>
about twice length of unguis, unguis and opposing seta of equal length.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA9B501FF99FF59FF4A8B51E229FA3C" blockId="72.[151,1437,151,1941]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FF4A8B51E6D7FBDC" box="[199,413,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Uropod 1 peduncle</emphasis>
dorsolateral margin with 3 small robust setae, dorsomedial margin with 4 long robust setae, 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FF1A8BB5E786FB01" box="[151,204,1159,1184]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">rami</emphasis>
slender, inner ramus 0.8 length of peduncle with 3 robust setae dorsodistally and strong terminal robust seta in hollow, outer ramus 0.9 length of inner ramus, naked except for strong terminal robust seta in hollow. 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FACB8B99E7EFFB48" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Uropod 2</emphasis>
peduncle half as long as 1, reaching as far as distal corner of urosomite 3, outer ramus about half as long as inner, naked, peduncle and inner ramus with 1 dorsal robust seta each. 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FC138BC1E343FAAC" box="[926,1033,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Uropod 3</emphasis>
peduncle about 0.6 as long as outer ramus, dorsodistal corner with group of 3 slender robust setae, outer ramus 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FC7F8A25E335FA90" box="[1010,1151,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">basal article</emphasis>
dorsolateral margin with 3 robust setae, dorsomedial margin with 3 or more robust setae, dorsodistal corner with 2 larger robust setae, short 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FF1A8A6DE67FFAD8" box="[151,309,1375,1401]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">second article</emphasis>
acutely pointed, with 3 robust setae of markedly different length, inner ramus as long as outer ramus basal article, with dorsal row of long setae in proximal half, apex with at least 1 long and 1 short robust setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA9B501FF99FF59FF4A8A95E6A6F9A8" blockId="72.[151,1437,151,1941]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FF4A8A95E65DFA60" box="[199,279,1447,1473]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Telson.</emphasis>
Length about 4 times greatest depth in lateral view, reaching to middle of uropod 3 rami, dorsal view length 3 times greatest width, each 
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FDA58AF9E512FA44" box="[552,600,1483,1509]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">lobe</emphasis>
with 1 mid-point and 1 distal robust setae, apices with group of 4 slender robust setae of varying length.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA9B501FF99FF59FF4A8921E3A7F98C" blockId="72.[151,1437,151,1941]" box="[199,1261,1555,1581]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FF4A8921E690F98C" box="[199,474,1555,1581]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Rows of elongate glands</emphasis>
present in uropod peduncles, adjacent parts of urosomites, and telson.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA9B501FF99FF59FF4A8904E5CBF9F0" blockId="72.[151,1437,151,1941]" box="[199,641,1590,1617]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FF4A8904E7BDF9F1" bold="true" box="[199,247,1590,1616]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Size</emphasis>
. Largest 
<specimenCount id="9D107E88FF99FF59FEED8905E63FF9F0" box="[352,373,1591,1617]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
, 
<quantity id="4CEE18E4FF99FF59FE0E8904E696F9F0" box="[387,476,1590,1617]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" unit="mm" value="4.5">4.5 mm</quantity>
. 
<specimenCount id="9D107E88FF99FF59FE6B8905E6B1F9F0" box="[486,507,1591,1617]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
not known.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30CE68AFF99FF59FF4A8968E531F9D4" box="[199,635,1626,1653]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BA9B501FF99FF59FF4A8968E531F9D4" blockId="72.[151,1437,151,1941]" box="[199,635,1626,1653]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FF4A8968E613F9D5" bold="true" box="[199,345,1626,1652]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Distribution</emphasis>
. NW 
<collectingCountry id="F301F591FF99FF59FE168969E54FF9D4" box="[411,517,1627,1653]" name="Australia" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Australia</collectingCountry>
; 
<quantity id="4CEE18E4FF99FF59FD9D8969E53CF9D4" box="[528,630,1627,1653]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.4" metricValueMax="8.4" metricValueMin="4.4" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" unit="m" value="64.0" valueMax="84.0" valueMin="44.0">
44– 
<specimenCount id="9D107E88FF99FF59FDB68969E53CF9D4" box="[571,630,1627,1653]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" type="generic">84 m</specimenCount>
</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30CE68AFF99FF59FF4A894DE529F834" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BA9B501FF99FF59FF4A894DE59CF888" blockId="72.[151,1437,151,1941]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FF4A894DE671F938" bold="true" box="[199,315,1663,1689]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C16CE82FF99FF59FECE894DE563F939" authorityName="Just" authorityYear="2022" box="[323,553,1663,1689]" class="Malacostraca" family="Synopiidae" genus="Pseudotiron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="miratus">
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FECE894DE563F939" box="[323,553,1663,1689]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Pseudotiron miratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C16CE82FF99FF59FD32894DE473F938" authorityName="Chevreux" authorityYear="1895" box="[703,825,1663,1689]" class="Malacostraca" family="Synopiidae" genus="Pseudotiron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bouvieri">
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FD32894DE473F938" box="[703,825,1663,1689]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">P. bouvieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the shape of the head, and in the truncate posterior projection of coxal plate 3 of the latter. 
<taxonomicName id="4C16CE82FF99FF59FDC08991E47BF91D" authorityName="Just" authorityYear="2022" box="[589,817,1699,1725]" class="Malacostraca" family="Synopiidae" genus="Pseudotiron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="miratus">
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FDC08991E47BF91D" box="[589,817,1699,1725]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Pseudotiron miratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shares with 
<taxonomicName id="4C16CE82FF99FF59FC368991E355F91C" authorityName="J. L. Barnard" authorityYear="1962" box="[955,1055,1699,1725]" class="Malacostraca" family="Synopiidae" genus="Pseudotiron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="golens">
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FC368991E355F91C" box="[955,1055,1699,1725]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">P. golens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the angularly projecting head, but the uropods of the latter are much shorter than in 
<taxonomicName id="4C16CE82FF99FF59FD3489F5E463F941" authorityName="Just" authorityYear="2022" box="[697,809,1735,1760]" class="Malacostraca" family="Synopiidae" genus="Pseudotiron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="miratus">
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FD3489F5E463F941" box="[697,809,1735,1760]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">P. miratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and the dactyli of pereopods 3–7 are distinctly elongate pre-stubby. 
<taxonomicName id="4C16CE82FF99FF59FE9189D9E695F8A5" authorityName="J. L. Barnard" authorityYear="1967" box="[284,479,1771,1797]" class="Malacostraca" family="Synopiidae" genus="Pseudotiron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coas">
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FE9189D9E695F8A5" box="[284,479,1771,1797]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Pseudotiron coas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from the other 3 species in its rectangular, non-pelagont coxal plate 3, and in having hardly any setae on pereopods and uropods.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA9B501FF99FF59FF4A8801E529F834" blockId="72.[151,1437,151,1941]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
Urosomal glands, as found in 
<taxonomicName id="4C16CE82FF99FF59FD9E8801E5BDF8ED" authorityName="Just" authorityYear="2022" box="[531,759,1843,1869]" class="Malacostraca" family="Synopiidae" genus="Pseudotiron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="miratus">
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FD9E8801E5BDF8ED" box="[531,759,1843,1869]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Pseudotiron miratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, have not been reported in the other 3 species in the genus. If it can be shown that these glands are absent in the 
<typeStatus id="54AD0BA3FF99FF59FD438865E5B4F8D0" box="[718,766,1879,1905]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">type</typeStatus>
species 
<taxonomicName id="4C16CE82FF99FF59FCD08865E24CF8D0" authority="Chevreux, 1895" authorityName="Chevreux" authorityYear="1895" box="[861,1286,1878,1905]" class="Malacostraca" family="Synopiidae" genus="Pseudotiron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bouvieri">
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FCD08865E303F8D0" box="[861,1097,1879,1905]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Pseudotiron bouvieri</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EF87C8F0FF99FF59FBDD8865E24CF8D0" author="Chevreux, E." box="[1104,1286,1878,1905]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" pagination="165 - 170" refId="ref48758" refString="Chevreux, E. (1895) Sur un Amphipode, Pseudotiron bouvieri, nov. gen. et sp., de la Famille des Syrrhoidae nouvelle pour la Fauna Mediterranenne. Bulletin de la Societe Zoologique de France, 20, 165 - 170. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 29691" type="journal article" year="1895">Chevreux, 1895</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, a new genus will be required for 
<taxonomicName id="4C16CE82FF99FF59FEFA8849E516F835" authorityName="Just" authorityYear="2022" box="[375,604,1915,1941]" class="Malacostraca" family="Synopiidae" genus="Pseudotiron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="miratus">
<emphasis id="B9626913FF99FF59FEFA8849E516F835" box="[375,604,1915,1941]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Pseudotiron miratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
